{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488757"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:55:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:55:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"526"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/526"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.06,0.06,0.05,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"526"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39576"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/526"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"526"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24032"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"446"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11614"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"846"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44254"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/39576"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 27-year-old Thai man presents concerned about a possible hereditary disease that appears to run in his family. He thinks he might have some sort of \u0027blood disorder\u0027 but is unable to provide any details. A haematological examination is normal, but the peripheral blood smear shows microspherocytes and eccentrocytes, with haemoglobin puddled to one side. The patient is advised on certain things he needs to avoid which could trigger problems.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most important that he avoid?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chloroquine","Penicillin","Broccoli","Peanut","Tetracycline"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has G6PD deficiency. This is an inborn error of metabolism that can lead to red cell destruction. The histological description of microspherocytes and eccentrocytes with puddling of the haemoglobin to one side is descriptive of \u0027bite cells\u0027 and \u0027blister cells\u0027 which are damaged by oxidative stress. The condition does not usually have any clinical manifestations, but certain triggers could lead to red cell breakdown, resulting in jaundice and dark urine. These triggers include a number of drugs and certain foodstuffs. The condition is prevalent in certain Asian and African countries. Broad beans (fava beans) are probably the best known trigger of a haemolytic crisis (favism). The anti-malarials, including \u003Cstrong\u003Echloroquine\u003C/strong\u003E, are well-recognised drugs that can precipitate a haemolytic crisis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Anti-malarial medications must be avoided in patients with G6PD deficiency."],"references":["Cappellini MD, Fiorelli G. Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency. Lancet 2008; 371:64-74."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24032"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"526"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/24032"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-09-26T19:55:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-09-26T19:55:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"526"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39576"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id